  "answer": "## Answer\nReAct-style agents keep reasoning and acting in one interleaved loop: the model emits reasoning traces and task actions together, and those traces are used to update plans, handle exceptions, and fetch external information. https://arxiv.org/abs/2210.03629\n\nPlanner-executor agents split that loop: a planner creates an explicit high-level or step-by-step plan, and an executor turns the plan into environment-specific actions or tool calls. https://docs.crewai.com/en/concepts/planning https://arxiv.org/abs/2503.09572\n\nTool-use implication: ReAct keeps tool observations inside the same evolving context as the reasoning trace, while planner-executor systems can isolate noisy execution details in the executor and preserve reasoning depth in the planner. https://microsoft.github.io/TaskWeaver/docs/advanced/telemetry/ https://arxiv.org/abs/2503.09572\n\nFailure modes differ: the ReAct paper highlights hallucination and error propagation, while Plan-and-Act says accurate plan generation is difficult because LLMs are not naturally trained for planning. https://arxiv.org/abs/2210.03629 https://arxiv.org/abs/2503.09572\n\nPractical recommendation: use ReAct when you want a simple reactive loop; prefer planner-executor for long-horizon, multi-step, tool-heavy tasks where explicit plans and role separation matter. That recommendation is an engineering inference from the cited sources, not a universal rule. https://openreview.net/forum?id=XUF5IBVAEB https://arxiv.org/abs/2509.10769\n\n### Required aspect coverage\n- interleaved reasoning and acting — covered by ReAct's interleaved reasoning/action loop. https://arxiv.org/abs/2210.03629\n- explicit planning stage — covered by CrewAI's step-by-step planning stage and Plan-and-Act's planner/executor split. https://docs.crewai.com/en/concepts/planning https://arxiv.org/abs/2503.09572\n- tool-use implications — covered by TaskWeaver's separated planner/executor/tool tracing. https://microsoft.github.io/TaskWeaver/docs/advanced/telemetry/\n- failure modes — covered by ReAct's hallucination/error propagation and Plan-and-Act's plan-generation difficulty. https://arxiv.org/abs/2210.03629 https://arxiv.org/abs/2503.09572\n- when each architecture is preferable — covered by PilotRL's long-horizon planning limitation for ReAct and AgentArch's model-specific architecture preferences. https://openreview.net/forum?id=XUF5IBVAEB https://arxiv.org/abs/2509.10769\n\n## Sources\n- ReAct: Synergizing Reasoning and Acting in Language Models — https://arxiv.org/abs/2210.03629\n- CrewAI Planning docs — https://docs.crewai.com/en/concepts/planning\n- TaskWeaver Telemetry docs — https://microsoft.github.io/TaskWeaver/docs/advanced/telemetry/\n- Plan-and-Act: Improving Planning of Agents for Long-Horizon Tasks — https://arxiv.org/abs/2503.09572\n- AgentArch: A Comprehensive Benchmark to Evaluate Agent Architectures in Enterprise — https://arxiv.org/abs/2509.10769\n- PilotRL: Training Language Model Agents via Global Planning-Guided Progressive Reinforcement Learning — https://openreview.net/forum?id=XUF5IBVAEB\n\n## Limitations\nThe preference guidance is a synthesis, not a universal law: AgentArch reports model-specific architectural preferences, and the long-horizon advantage of planner-executor is context-dependent. https://arxiv.org/abs/2509.10769 https://arxiv.org/abs/2503.09572\nI did not find a single canonical peer-reviewed head-to-head paper that cleanly isolates only ReAct versus planner-executor across all domains; the comparison here comes from the ReAct paper, planning/framework docs, and architecture/long-horizon benchmarks. https://arxiv.org/abs/2210.03629 https://docs.crewai.com/en/concepts/planning https://arxiv.org/abs/2509.10769"
